{"author": "Max A. Cherney", "tick": "", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/techs-500-billion-club-has-tripled-and-it-dominates-the-market-as-earnings-storm-approaches-2018-01-30", "head": "These six tech companies are worth $500 billion, and their earnings are about to sway the market - MarketWatch", "text": "Published: Apple and Alphabet have been joined in the $500 billion club by Microsoft, Facebook, Amazon and Alibaba By As 2017 dawned, two tech companies were worth $500 billion on their own. That number has since tripled, forming a group of half a dozen tech companies worth at least half a trillion dollars that dominate the markets as their products weave their way into every facet of consumers\u2019 lives. All six companies \u2014 Alibaba Group Holding Ltd. , Alphabet Inc.  , Amazon.com Inc. , Apple Inc. , Facebook Inc. and Microsoft Corp. \u2014 will report earnings on Wednesday and Thursday, and their size means the final tabulation of their 2017 performances will have an enormous effect on the market. The size of these companies have shifted the weight of the S&P 500 index , with five of them now accounting for nearly a quarter of the benchmark index, 22% to 23% according to , senior index analyst for S&P Indices. Alibaba is . Today, Silverblatt says, tech stocks are where the market\u2019s explosive growth lies, and that's what the current top-heavy index signals. \u201cTechnology is a growing area,\u201d he said. \u201cThis is the quick and easy money.\u201d    Still, it is nowhere near the outsize effect of Big Tech during the dot-com boom in the late 1990s. Silverblatt pointed out that the top seven tech companies then accounted for more than a third of the index, 34%, dominated by companies like AOL Inc., General Electric Co. , International Business Machines Corp. and a company still in the top tier, Microsoft. Microsoft was the big dog back then, accounting for 4.92% of the S&P 500 index in 1999; Apple, the most valuable company of the current era, accounts for 3.63%. \u201cEven though we\u2019re top-heavy, it\u2019s not the same magnitude,\u201d Silverblatt said in a telephone interview. It is still top-heavy enough to make this week\u2019s earnings reports from the $500 billion club crucial. A combined value of more than $4 trillion is at stake heading into Wednesday and Thursday\u2019s raft of results: Microsoft and Facebook report Wednesday afternoon, Alibaba on Thursday morning, and Alphabet, Amazon and Alibaba on Thursday afternoon.          Daniel Ives, head of technology research at GBH Insights, said that the group\u2019s current stock prices are based on expectations that these companies will report huge holiday-shopping quarters. \u201cThe street is expecting clean beats,\u201d Ives said over the phone. Today\u2019s tech giants are well-positioned to continue to grow because of consumer trends as well as smart bets by executives, Ives said. And at least one, if not a handful, of these companies will crack the $1 trillion mark in 12 to 18 months, he predicted, throwing off any doubts collected along the way. \u201cEven though everyone is in love with them, the skeptics continue to wait for the fall,\u201d he said. \u201cBut they have phenomenal business models, great management teams, and a market that appreciates the potential for the next three to five years. I don\u2019t see anything getting in the way of these names.\u201d Max A. Cherney is a MarketWatch technology reporter based in San Francisco. Follow him on Twitter @chernandburn. Max A. Cherney is a MarketWatch technology reporter based in San Francisco. Follow him on Twitter @chernandburn. Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and ."}
{"author": "SA Editor Brandy Betz", "tick": "", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/news/3326868-bmo-downgrades-apple-expects-revenue-guidance-cut?source=marketwatch", "head": "BMO downgrades Apple, expects revenue guidance cut - Apple Inc. (NASDAQ:AAPL) | Seeking Alpha", "text": "BMO Capital Markets Apple (NASDAQ: ) from Outperform to Market Perform on expectations the company will cut its revenue forecast in tomorrow\u2019s earnings report. Analyst Tim Long cites press reports of iPhone X order mix and says \u201cwe believe a weaker mix in Q1 will push estimates lower for March and beyond.\u201d Long expects Apple to guide meaningfully lower \u201con the order of $5-$6B compared to consensus revenue estimates.\u201d Price target lowered from $199 to $162, a 3% downside on yesterday\u2019s close. Apple shares are to $168. Previously: (Jan. 22) Previously: (Jan. 17) Now read:"}
{"author": null, "tick": "", "link": "https://investorplace.com/2018/01/is-netflix-inc-nflx-stock-rally-overdone/", "head": "Is Netflix, Inc. Stock's Rally Overdone? | InvestorPlace", "text": "Menu Gaining more than 40% over the course of a year is a fantastic performance for most companies, but for leading streaming service (NASDAQ: ) it\u2019s just a simple month\u2019s work. You read that right. Less than one month into 2018, Netflix stock is up a whopping 41%. And that\u2019s on top of the 55% return the stock enjoyed in 2017. As a member of the famed FAANG group \u2014 (NASDAQ: ), (NASDAQ: ), (NASDAQ: ), Netflix and (NASDAQ: , NASDAQ: ) \u2014 the company is often compared to the other technology darlings when it comes to performance and valuation. But in reality, there is no true competitor to NFLX. There is no other company even in the same stratosphere as far as popularity and business model goes. From a valuation perspective, NFLX stock is trading with a forward price-to-earnings ratio of 62.9, which I\u2019ll admit does sound high at first. However, because of the company\u2019s above-average earnings growth, its PEG (price-to-earnings/growth) ratio is very acceptable at 1.2 \u2014 well below the market average. The actual earnings numbers are impressive as well. Wall Street expects the bottom line to come in at $2.66 a share in 2018 and explode to $8.83 a share by 2021. It\u2019s common knowledge that earnings drive stock prices over the long run, but when it comes to Netflix there are a few other metrics that investors also love to analyze. Subscriber growth is actually the most important factor for companies that generate revenue from subscription fees. NFLX added 8.3 million new streaming members in the recently reported fourth quarter, bringing the total up to 117.6 million. Management had previously forecasted 6.3 million new subscribers, so the huge beat \u2014 which included better-than-expected results both domestically and abroad \u2014 was a surprise to investors. It was also likely the reason for the big gap up in the shares after the report was released. Revenue is another key metric here \u2014 and for any company that is still in the early stages of having its cash flow to the bottom line. Netflix\u2019s top-line result was better than expected in the fourth quarter and showed growth of 32.6% year-over-year. It was also better than the third quarter\u2019s 30.3% increase. Accelerating revenue growth attracts money and therefore leads to higher share prices over time. Looking at the chart, there\u2019s no question that NFLX stock is overbought in the short term. But that shouldn\u2019t be surprising after such a strong and quick run. I do expect a brief pullback in the near term, but after that, the stock will once again be a buying opportunity. My long-term outlook is bullish on Netflix stock and I believe that reaching the $300 milestone is certainly possible in 2018. Article printed from InvestorPlace Media, https://investorplace.com/2018/01/is-netflix-inc-nflx-stock-rally-overdone/. \u00a92018 InvestorPlace Media, LLC  \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7   \u00b7    Financial Market Data powered by FinancialContent Services, Inc. All rights reserved. Nasdaq quotes delayed at least 15 minutes, all others at least 20 minutes. Copyright \u00a9 2018 InvestorPlace Media, LLC. All rights reserved. 9201 Corporate Blvd, Rockville, MD 20850."}
{"author": "Ashraf Eassa", "tick": "", "link": "https://www.fool.com/investing/2018/01/31/apple-inc-rumored-to-be-working-on-4-new-iphones-f.aspx?source=djc&utm_campaign=article&utm_medium=feed&utm_source=djc", "head": "\n            \n    Apple Inc. Rumored to Be Working on 4 New iPhones for 2018 -- The Motley Fool\n\n        ", "text": "Founded in 1993 by brothers Tom and David Gardner, The Motley Fool helps millions of people attain financial freedom through our website, podcasts, books, newspaper column, radio show, and premium investing services. According to , has been hard at work on four new iPhones. The devices include the following: OLED displays offer some significant image quality and speed benefits compared to LCDs, but OLED displays are harder to manufacture and there are fewer suppliers of them. Both factors ultimately make OLED displays more expensive than LCDs. Image source: Apple. Apple had previously been rumored to be working on three new iPhone models for 2018 -- one with a 5.85-inch OLED display, one with a 6.46-inch OLED display, and a lower-cost model with a 6.1-inch LCD. Two of the previously rumored models show up in\u00a0DIGITIMES Research's set of future iPhones (current rumors point to a as well as a in development), but this list seems to have two models that haven't really been talked about before -- the 5.7- to 5.8-inch LCD iPhone and the 6- to 6.1-inch OLED iPhone. On top of that,\u00a0DIGITIMES Research says that Apple is now leaning toward releasing two LCD-based iPhones this year (the 5.7- to 5.8-inch model as well as the 6- to 6.1-inch model) alongside a single OLED-based iPhone -- the one with the jumbo-sized 6.46-inch display. Apple had, according the report, previously been planning to release the two OLED iPhones as well as the 6.1-inch LCD model. Here's why these claims seem suspect. One of the best-connected Apple analysts is KGI Securities' Ming-Chi Kuo. According to Kuo, Apple is planning to launch two OLED-based iPhones this year -- one with a 5.85-inch OLED display (the same as the one on the current iPhone X) and one with a 6.46-inch OLED display (effectively a larger version of the successor to the current iPhone X). In addition to those two iPhones, Kuo also says Apple is planning a phone with a 6.1-inch LCD for more price-sensitive smartphone shoppers. Considering that Kuo has been steadily releasing detailed specifications of these devices for quite some time, and considering Kuo's considerable Apple supply chain connections, I'd be much more comfortable betting on Kuo's information than virtually any other analyst's. Admittedly the argument above might not be all that convincing to some -- I'm essentially saying that one source is probably more reliable than the other, but the reality is that sometimes reliable sources get things wrong and relatively unknown sources can get things totally right. To that end, I think it's worth thinking through these claims from a business/marketing perspective. Image source: Apple. When Apple introduced the iPhone X, it made quite a big deal about the work that it put into the OLED display that the device uses. On top of that, the lack of OLED displays on iPhones had been a competitive disadvantage (perceived or otherwise) for Apple for quite some time. The move to an OLED display and the significant marketing that Apple has invested in extolling the virtues of the technology make it seem quite unlikely that Apple would use an inferior technology on two of its three upcoming flagship devices -- again -- and limit OLED technology to a single premium model. Apple was forced to limit OLED technology to a single model in the 2017 iPhone lineup, likely due to cost and capacity constraints, but it's unlikely those constraints will persist into the next product cycle, especially as Apple brings (Apple has only a single OLED display supplier for the current iPhone X). Apple would be hurting its competitive positioning by not expanding its use of OLED display technology in the 2018 iPhones. The final thing to keep in mind is that iPhone development cycles are long and Apple relies on many suppliers for critical components. The reality is that because of the sheer scale that Apple operates at, it needs to work with its suppliers years in advance on technology development. On top of that, Apple's suppliers need to have some idea of how much component demand Apple will need for a product cycle well in advance so that they can build the appropriate manufacturing capacity. At this point, it's highly likely that Apple's OLED display suppliers ( and possibly ) have already been given some indication as to how much demand Apple expects for its 2018 iPhones. Those companies need to make sure that they put the appropriate capacity in to support the cycle. If Apple were to decide at the last minute to switch from releasing two OLED-based iPhones and one LCD model in 2018 to one OLED model and two LCD models, then that'd potentially leave Apple's OLED suppliers holding a pretty big bag. On top of that, there may not be enough capacity in place at Apple's key LCD suppliers to meet its demand, especially on such short notice. Ashraf Eassa is a technology specialist with The Motley Fool. He writes mostly about technology stocks, but is especially interested in anything related to chips -- the semiconductor kind, that is. He can be reached on Twitter -- follow him there:"}
{"author": "Bill Maurer", "tick": "", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4141667-apple-panic-really-warranted?source=marketwatch", "head": "Apple Panic Really Warranted? - Apple Inc. (NASDAQ:AAPL) | Seeking Alpha", "text": "Fiscal Q2 estimates continue to drop ahead of earnings. Do long-term holders care if growth is 21% or 25%? Don't forget the power of a weaker US dollar. Nobody should be surprised by the panic we are seeing when it comes to street analysts regarding Apple ( ) ahead of Thursday's earnings report. Not only is this a theme that seems to happen almost every quarter as earnings approach, but I started warning investors on the iPhone X back in December. Over the last few days, we've finally seen a large adjustment to analyst estimates, which has taken down the stock as seen below. But is this panic really warranted? ( I cautioned investors that analysts would take down their estimates , and that scenario is playing out exactly as I figured it would. The biggest pillar of this week's panic is a report that Apple is cutting iPhone X production to 20 million units in the current quarter. You can read all about that as well as multiple analyst notes on the situation . The chart below shows how estimates have accelerated downward recently, with still more than a day to go until Apple gives guidance for the March ending period. ( The current figure still is a bit misleading, however, something you'd know if you read my recent or some of my past coverage. This is because the high estimate on the street calls for more than $83 billion in revenues for the fiscal Q2 period, which is either a really bullish analyst or perhaps a typo estimate that should have been included in Q1. Taking this estimate out completely drops the overall consensus by about $600 million, which will make Apple's guidance look a lot better. I want to illustrate an example of how things could look for the March period, so to do that I looked at some of Apple's recent results. In the left box below, you can see the main highlights of Apple's March ending period from last year, and the right box shows the reported growth rates seen in the last quarterly report we have on record, which ended in September 2017. ( The iPad has been making a bit of a comeback, and Apple last year in an effort to combat soaring memory prices, so even in a bear case let's think about a 5% revenue increase, which is still only one-third of what we saw in the September period. Likewise, we'll assume a 10% increase for Mac revenues, which will be helped by . Services have been running around a 20% growth rate for most quarters (the 34% above was partially due to a one-time adjustment if you remember), so we'll throw that into the model. Other products also should do nicely thanks to the strength of the Apple Watch as well as nearly two months of initial HomePod sales, so I'll throw 20% in for a conservative growth rate there. That gets me back to the iPhone, which sold over 50.76 million units last year. Let's assume absolutely no growth, but that 20 million units are the iPhone X we are hearing about. I'll model $1,050 as an average selling price for the blended X sales, along with a $630 ASP for the other 30 million or so units, which is a drop of roughly $25 over last year. Combining all of this gets me to a revenue number of about $62.8 billion for the March period. That would be right in the middle of the predicted $62-$64 billion range for guidance from analyst Tony Sacconaghi, in on Tuesday. Again, however, some of those numbers seem fairly conservative. What if the iPad comes in with a 10% revenue growth rate, or the Mac comes in at 15%? What if services and other products grow more than I expected? I could easily add another billion or so to my base case. This also assumes that overall iPhone unit sales are flat. What if they grow even a couple of percent? Finally, there is one other major elephant in the room that nobody seems to be discussing in all of this: The weaker US dollar. The chart below shows a roughly 10% decline in the dollar index over the past year, with some currencies showing even more strength against the greenback than that. When foreign results are translated into US dollars, a weaker dollar helps Apple. If you take half of a $62 billion quarter (last year's Q2 saw 60% of sales outside of the Americas) and improve it by even 5% overall to adjust for a weaker dollar, that's over a billion and a half dollars right there. ( Here's the real question that investors have to ask themselves when looking at what Apple gives for guidance tomorrow. If you are a long-term investor, not someone just looking to make a quick buck, does it really matter if revenue guidance is for growth 19.1% ($63 billion) or 24.8% ($66 billion)? Does a few extra percentage points of growth in any one quarter really matter to whether or not you should hold Apple shares over the next 5-10 years? There are plenty of reasons to be positive on the future, like the massive capital return plan, lower tax rates, etc. Also, you have to take into consideration the pullback in Apple shares from $180 to $167 currently. As we get closer to Apple's Thursday earnings report, there is a full blown panic when it comes to the tech giant. Analysts are racing to lower estimates thanks to potentially poor iPhone X sales, but are they ignoring the bigger picture? Even if Apple guidance is in the low to mid $60 billion range, we're still talking about a revenue growth rate of around or slightly above 20%, which is very strong for a company of this size. Apple shares have come well off their highs recently, so you're not paying an all-time high for the stock. Those looking at the bright future might actually consider this pullback as one to take advantage of. I really don't think this panic is fully warranted, but what do you think?   I wrote this article myself, and it expresses my own opinions. I am not receiving compensation for it (other than from Seeking Alpha). I have no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article. Investors are always reminded that before making any investment, you should do your own proper due diligence on any name directly or indirectly mentioned in this article. Investors should also consider seeking advice from a broker or financial adviser before making any investment decisions. Any material in this article should be considered general information, and not relied on as a formal investment recommendation. The chat platform is currently undergoing maintenance. To see the chat, try to refresh in about 5-10 minutes. Chat is not supported in your browser version. Please upgrade your browser or use a different browser, such as Google Chrome. You do not have permissions for this room."}
{"author": "Rich Smith", "tick": "", "link": "https://www.fool.com/investing/2018/01/31/apple-stock-downgraded-ahead-of-earnings-what-you.aspx?source=djc&utm_campaign=article&utm_medium=feed&utm_source=djc", "head": "\n            \n    Apple Stock Downgraded Ahead of Earnings: What You Need to Know -- The Motley Fool\n\n        ", "text": "Founded in 1993 by brothers Tom and David Gardner, The Motley Fool helps millions of people attain financial freedom through our website, podcasts, books, newspaper column, radio show, and premium investing services. We're still a day away from getting earnings news from  -- but one analyst isn't waiting for the shoe to drop. This morning, Canadian investment bank announced it is downgrading Apple -- ahead of earnings, but not necessarily of what it thinks Apple earned. Here are the three things you need to know. Image source: Getty Images. Let's start with the basics. BMO Capital lowered its outperform rating on Apple to market perform, and cut its price target on Apple stock by nearly 20%, to $162 per share. If BMO's right, that means that Apple at $167 and change today is selling for about 3% more than the stock is worth. Not coincidentally, this same morning we read in the pages of (subscription required) that getting its fans to ante up $999 to buy its top-of-the-line . Apple initially planned to build 40 million iPhone Xs in Q1 2018, says the . Instead, demand for the device has been so weak that Apple is cutting that production target in half, to just 20 million phones. (The situation could be even worse than that. quotes other sources saying that Apple has cut component orders for iPhone X by 60%, implying Apple could be missing its sales target by than half.) BMO believes that \"order cuts for iPhone X\" \"will push [sales] estimates lower for March and beyond\" at Apple. But BMO sees even bigger problems ahead for Apple stock than simply one underwhelming product launch. As the analyst explains, Apple's failure to get consumers to pay $999 for a smartphone may mark a \"secular change\" in Apple's business model that depends on convincing consumers (many of whom already own iPhones) to buy ever-pricier models. In BMO's view, iPhones as a family of devices may be approaching, or may even have reached, a ceiling at which \"prices will plateau as with the rest of the industry.\" If this is the case, then going forward, Apple may need to rely on selling more iPhone units to grow its profits, rather than selling mostly replacement iPhones at ever-higher prices. That could be a problem as BMO notes that Apple may be losing share in the important Chinese market. BMO believes that in the December quarter that Apple will report on tomorrow, iPhone sales were flat (by dollar value), and shipments down 9% (by units). What will happen if BMO is right -- if Apple is no longer able to hike prices but must rather \"plateau\" them on falling unit sales? And what will happen if this trend expands beyond China to the world at large? Even with higher prices (which BMO notes have been climbing steadily for \"10 years\"), it's worth pointing out that Apple's gross, operating, and net margins all began falling about two years ago. Annual operating margin has taken a particular hit, declining 370 basis points since fiscal 2015. Data from show operating margin was 30.5% that year, but fell to just 26.8% in fiscal 2017 (which ended last quarter) -- and are far below the 35%-ish margins seen in Apple's heyday in 2012. If BMO is right, Apple may have trouble using higher prices to counter this trend of declining profit margin. If BMO is right, Apple stock may have finally peaked."}
{"author": null, "tick": "", "link": "https://www.benzinga.com/analyst-ratings/analyst-color/18/01/11109390/bofa-dont-write-off-apples-hardware-business-just-yet?utm_campaign=partner_feed&utm_source=marketwatch.com&utm_medium=web_click&utm_content=ticker_page", "head": "BofA: Don't Write Off Apple  (NASDAQ:AAPL)'s Hardware Business Just Yet | Benzinga", "text": "(NASDAQ: )'s valuation implies a \" \" moving forward, but this is unwarranted, according to Bank of America Merrill Lynch. Bank of America's maintains a Buy rating on with an unchanged $220 price objective. Apple's stock is valued under the assumption that the company will see undergo a decline in hardware sales growth, Mohan said in a Tuesday note. (See the analyst's track record .) This thinking is \"too pessimistic\" and the hardware business has a multiyear growth trajectory driven by growth in the average selling price in 2018 and 2019, and a potential new iPhone in 2020 with 5G, artificial reality and virtual reality. Sales of other hardware devices \u2014 including AirPods, HomePod and Apple Watch \u2014 remain strong. Here is the analyst's sum-of-the-parts valuation based on bull, base and bear cases: \"Given the stock is trading at $168, in our opinion the stock is already discounting a declining hardware business and much worse than run rate services business, which is too pessimistic in our opinion,\" Mohan said. Shares of Apple were trading higher by 0.4 percent Wednesday morning.            "}
{"author": "Gregor Stuart Hunter ", "tick": "", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/asia-pacific-markets-slide-after-wall-street-stumbles-2018-01-29", "head": "Asia-Pacific markets slide after Wall Street stumbles - MarketWatch", "text": "Published: Nikkei on track for 5th straight loss; bank stocks weigh on Hang Seng By Asia-Pacific equity markets followed U.S. stock benchmarks lower as global government borrowing costs continued to rise. Indexes in the region hit session lows by midday, with Japan\u2019s Nikkei Stock Average falling 1.5%. Benchmarks in Taiwan , Hong Kong and Australia were each nearly 1% lower in recent trading. The Nikkei, on track for its first five-day losing streak since November, slid as the dollar pulled back from session highs against the Japanese yen at around \u00a5109.20. The dollar was recently around \u00a5108.70. Taiwan, where many Apple suppliers are based, weakened after the tech giant\u2019s shares fell 2.1% Monday amid fresh speculation about potential iPhone production cuts. The company will report earnings on Thursday in the U.S. Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. , the island\u2019s biggest company, fell 2%. The Hang Seng Index , meanwhile, was hurt by two of its recent top performers\u2014China Construction Bank and Industrial & Commercial Bank of China . The city\u2019s two biggest lenders each fell 3%, making up half of the index\u2019s decline. Some investors are becoming more cautious about equities, analysts say. Valuations and volumes have surged above average recently, which means global markets could be primed to reverse course, said Robert Gillam, chief executive of McKinley Capital, an Alaska-based investment management firm that oversees $6.4 billion in assets. \u201cAm I worried for the immediate term? Sure,\u201d he said. \u201cThe world is definitely due for a pullback.\u201d Capital Economics said emerging-market stocks\u2019 \u201cflying start\u201d to 2018 isn\u2019t likely to last. \u201cWe forecast that China\u2019s economy will slow in the coming months,\u201d it said, adding that it is unlikely that growth rebounds in smaller emerging-market economies such as Brazil will pick up the slack. Elsewhere, President Donald Trump will deliver his first State of the Union address in less than 24 hours and 10-year Treasury yields, recently at 2.72%, are at their highest in nearly four years. The yield on 10-year German government bonds, known as bunds, was last at 0.69%, the highest level in almost three years. American inflation data for December fell below its target and showed a slight loss in momentum. Still, Fed-fund futures were showing no chance of a rate increase by the Federal Open Market Committee; its two-day meeting begins Tuesday. The next increase isn\u2019t expected until March. The global oil benchmark was recently 0.5% lower in Asia trading. Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and ."}
{"author": "Paulo Santos", "tick": "", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4141672-amazon-surpasses-apple-valuable-business-earth?source=marketwatch", "head": "Amazon Surpasses Apple As Most Valuable Business On Earth - Apple Inc. (NASDAQ:AAPL) | Seeking Alpha", "text": "Amazon.com just became the most valuable business on Earth. You won't see it in the news. There's an explanation, and some other implications. This is a headline you won\u2019t read today, unless I write it. Yes, Amazon ( ) has just surpassed Apple ( ) for the title of \u201cmost valuable business on earth.\u201d Looking only at market capitalization, you wouldn\u2019t know that. Hence, you won\u2019t be seeing it in headlines elsewhere. However, a business\u2019 value isn\u2019t measured by market cap. Instead, it\u2019s measured by EV (enterprise value), which removes the effect from how that business is financed. It so happens that Apple carries a lot of net cash, whereas carries a tiny bit of debt, and that makes all the difference. Consider the following: Amazon.com surpassing Apple is in and of itself news. It also speaks about how differently the market values these two companies, and indeed how news impact them so differently. But more on that later. It gets old hat to refer to it, but Amazon.com carries an historically record price/earnings for companies this size. Never in history has the largest, most valuable busines raded for current-year earnings. We don\u2019t even need to look at the books to know that. Large, profitable companies during the dot.com years had trouble even reaching 100x earnings. This is a whole new page. Apple, for its part, carries a middling valuation. Unremarkable. Some will say it\u2019s cheap, some will say it\u2019s fair. It trades for 14.5x FY2018 earnings consensus. This valuation comes with the over-reliance on the iPhone. It's hard to build a higher multiple when the iPhone X gets on the news every day, with proclamations that it\u2019s under-performing sales expectations. Not that expectations have mattered much here. Amazon entered 2017 with . Right now, before it reports Q4 2017, those same expectations have been cut in more than half to $4.32. One can only wonder what would have happened to Apple stock if it had endured the same. To put it simply, over one year Amazon.com's shares were more than halved while the stock nearly doubled. The truth of the matter is that Amazon.com is perhaps the very first business to attain the largest-ever valuation entirely based on fuzzy hopes for the future. Amazon.com has two extraordinary businesses, AWS and 3P (Third-Party marketplace) retail. But it also has a tremendously unprofitable business called \u201ceverything else\u201d (though the overwhelming majority of it is first-party retail). The ethereal promise from these businesses has, for the first time ever, vanquished the hard realities of profit, as presented by Apple. Apple\u2019s $11.5 per share expectations translate roughly to $60 billion in expected profits. Amazon.com\u2019s $4.32 translates to $2.1 billion. The profits David beats the profits Goliath even though the odds were 28.5:1. Nowhere can the market\u2019s blind faith in Amazon.com be seen more clearly than how Amazon.com often reacts to news: Perhaps the market was mesmerized by this initiative\u2019s intent to be nonprofit. It immediately connected it to Amazon.com or something. Because as UnitedHealth was clocked, only Amazon.com\u2019s stock rose. Both Berkshire Hathaway and JPMorgan were down on the day. Are they the junior irrelevant partners? It wouldn\u2019t even seem that way, with Berkshire allocating Todd Combs to the initiative (by the way, is this a promotion or demotion?). In overall terms, my conclusion here is that Amazon.com is just the largest market capitalization company being inflated by a very obvious stock market bubble. A bubble now trying to compete with the dot.com bubble, and exceeding it in places. This bubble exceeds the dotcom bubble in: Having said this, this isn\u2019t a call to sell short Amazon.com or anything like that. Who knows how large the whole thing will get? While runs and runs, the fact is that its EPS estimates don\u2019t move. As a result, if its prospects have indeed become so much brighter during the last three months, then facing unchanged estimates would make for an easier beat.   I wrote this article myself, and it expresses my own opinions. I am not receiving compensation for it (other than from Seeking Alpha). I have no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article. The chat platform is currently undergoing maintenance. To see the chat, try to refresh in about 5-10 minutes. Chat is not supported in your browser version. Please upgrade your browser or use a different browser, such as Google Chrome. You do not have permissions for this room."}
{"author": "Emily Bary", "tick": "", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/apple-to-hold-off-on-certain-new-iphone-software-features-in-attempt-to-focus-on-performance-improvements-2018-01-30", "head": "Apple to hold off on certain new iPhone software features in attempt to focus on performance improvements: report - MarketWatch", "text": "Published: By Apple Inc. is pushing back plans for several software feature enhancements on the iPhone as it focuses on improving \"performance and quality issues,\" on Tuesday. The story said that Apple will delay making improvements to areas such as the mail app, photo-editing software, and the home screen until 2019. The company will still move forward with plans to enhance augmented-reality features and add new parental-control options, Axios said, noting that Apple's software chief Craig Federighi announced the new priorities to employees during a meeting in early January. Apple has come under pressure over the last few weeks after the company said in response to consumer complaints that it intentionally slowed down older iPhone batteries. Shares of Apple are down 1.4% in premarket trading. The stock is up 38% over the past 12 months, compared with a 32% gain for the Dow Jones Industrial Average  Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and ."}
